    "text": "MemoryWAM uses a hybrid memory design that combines recent frames, event-boundary anchor frames, and compact gist tokens that summarize long-range history.",
    "topic": "Memory design of MemoryWAM"
  },
  {
    "text": "A tailored attention mechanism in MemoryWAM enables retrieval of both detailed short-term context and compressed long-term context.",
    "topic": "Attention mechanism in MemoryWAM"
  },
  {
    "text": "MemoryWAM outperforms strong vision-language-action (VLA) and WAM baselines on long-horizon, memory-dependent manipulation tasks in both simulation and the real world.",
    "topic": "Performance of MemoryWAM"
  },
  {
    "text": "MemoryWAM maintains favorable computational efficiency with reduced inference latency and GPU memory usage compared to methods that preserve long histories.",
    "topic": "Computational efficiency of MemoryWAM"
  },
  {
    "text": "Existing WAMs face a trade-off between efficient inference (conditioning only on recent observations) and preserving long histories (incurring high time and space costs).",
    "topic": "Trade-off in existing WAMs"
  }
